    faithJourney:
      "Belshazzar didn't have a faith journey in any devotional sense — he had a collision with the God of Israel, and it lasted about one evening. Unlike his predecessor Nebuchadnezzar, who at least went through a prolonged process of humiliation and eventual acknowledgment of God's sovereignty, Belshazzar received no second chance. The text presents him as someone who knew the Nebuchadnezzar story — Daniel explicitly reminds him of it — and chose defiance anyway. He had the case study sitting right there in the family history and decided the lesson didn't apply to him.\n\nWhat's honest to say about Belshazzar's relationship to Israel's God is this: he knew enough to be accountable. He wasn't an ignorant pagan stumbling into a theological dispute. He deliberately desecrated the temple vessels, which means he understood their significance well enough to use them as a provocation. His story sits in Scripture not as a conversion narrative but as a warning about the specific danger of having access to truth and treating it with contempt. The handwriting wasn't written in a language Belshazzar couldn't learn — it was written in a language he'd never bothered to take seriously.",
