    faithJourney:
      "Cyrus's relationship to Israel's God is one of the Bible's most fascinating loose ends. Isaiah 45:4 says it plainly: \"I call you by name... though you do not know me.\" Cyrus was God's instrument without being God's worshiper. He almost certainly remained a Zoroastrian or a polytheist who honored Marduk in Babylon and Ahura Mazda in Persia. The text makes no effort to claim otherwise. What it claims is something more radical: that God's sovereignty extends so far beyond Israel's borders that a foreign king with no covenant relationship can be called \"anointed\" and fulfill divine purposes without personal conversion.\n\nThis is uncomfortable for anyone who wants a tidy equation between knowing God and being used by God. Cyrus didn't pray to Yahweh. He didn't observe the Sabbath. He probably couldn't have picked Jerusalem out on a map before his intelligence briefings. But when Jewish grandparents who had been born in captivity finally walked back through the gates of their ancestral city, it was because of his signature on a decree. His story invites a question the Bible never fully resolves: What does it mean when God works through someone who doesn't know God? The answer seems to be that it happens more often than the faithful find comfortable.",
