    faithJourney:
      "Vashti's story contains no explicit theology. She's a Persian queen, not an Israelite, and the book of Esther itself famously never mentions God. But Vashti's refusal sits at the very beginning of a book that is entirely about providence working through human decisions. Her \"no\" creates the vacancy that leads to Esther's elevation, which leads to the salvation of the Jewish people. Whether Vashti knew it or had any concept of it, her choice to protect her own integrity set in motion a chain of events that preserved an entire nation.\n\nThere's a kind of faith operating in Vashti's refusal, even if it's not religious faith in any traditional sense. It's a trust that some principles are worth more than the positions they cost you. She didn't know that her deposition would lead anywhere meaningful. She just knew that being paraded before a room of drunk men wasn't something she was willing to do, crown or no crown. That intuition — that some things matter more than survival — is the same raw material that religious faith is built on, even when it shows up in someone who never enters a synagogue or a temple.",
