    bioBrief:
      'A post-exilic prophet who delivered a blunt, urgent message to the returned exiles: stop paneling your own houses and rebuild God\'s temple. His short book — just two chapters — got the stalled construction project moving again.',
    bioFull:
      "Haggai is the prophet with the shortest book and the most practical message. No apocalyptic visions, no extended poetry, no mysterious symbolism — just a direct, almost annoyed question: \"Is it time for you to live in your paneled houses while this house lies in ruins?\" The returned exiles had been back from Babylon for about eighteen years. They'd started rebuilding the temple, ran into opposition, got discouraged, and then — here's the honest part — got comfortable. They built their own houses. They planted their own gardens. The temple foundation sat there like a half-finished renovation everyone walks past and says they'll get to next month.\n\nHaggai's genius is that he doesn't just shame them. He connects their neglect of the temple to their economic struggles: \"You earn wages, only to put them in a purse with holes.\" It's not a mystical curse — it's a diagnosis. You're investing everything in your own comfort and wondering why nothing feels like enough. The community has no center, no shared project, no common purpose, and the resulting emptiness is showing up in their bank accounts and their harvests. That's not magic; that's what happens when a community stops investing in anything bigger than individual survival.\n\nThink of Haggai as the community organizer who walks into a neighborhood where everyone has remodeled their kitchens but the community center has been boarded up for two decades. He doesn't give a sermon — he gives a budget presentation. \"You spent $40,000 on your kitchen. You gave $200 to the community fund. And you're wondering why the neighborhood doesn't feel like a neighborhood anymore. Here's your answer.\"\n\nHis message worked. Within twenty-three days of his first oracle, the construction resumed. The temple was completed four years later. Haggai is proof that sometimes the most prophetic thing you can say is the most obvious thing no one wants to hear.",
    modernParallel:
      "Haggai is the pastor of a suburban church who stands up one Sunday and says, \"We've spent $2 million on the new fellowship hall but we haven't funded the food pantry in three years. I'd like us to sit with that for a minute.\" He's the nonprofit director who looks at a room of donors living in $800,000 homes and asks why the after-school program still can't afford a full-time teacher.\n\nMore specifically, he's the financial advisor who tells a couple, \"You make $180,000 a year, you spend $175,000 on lifestyle, you give $1,200 to charity, and you've been telling me for five years that you feel like something's missing. I can see what's missing. It's in your spreadsheet.\"",
