    faithJourney:
      "Haggai's faith was the faith of a man who could see misplaced priorities and refused to be polite about them. He didn't arrive with grand theology — he arrived with an observation. The people were busy, productive, and spiritually stalled. Their faith had become private and individual, and the communal expression of it — the temple, the shared worship, the visible commitment to something beyond personal comfort — had been quietly abandoned. Haggai's contribution was to say out loud what everyone already knew and no one wanted to admit.\n\nWhat makes Haggai's faith interesting is that it was deeply material. He didn't separate the spiritual from the economic. In his view, the community's failure to invest in the temple wasn't just a religious oversight — it was an economic disorder. A society that invests only in private comfort and neglects shared sacred space will find that even the private comfort stops satisfying. That's not a mystical claim; it's an observation that any sociologist would recognize. Haggai's faith was rooted in the conviction that the material and the spiritual are woven together, and that you can't neglect one without the other unraveling.",
    sourceTier: 'ai_assisted',
    sourceNotes:
      'Source: Book of Haggai (2 chapters). One of the most precisely dated books in the OT — all oracles dated to the second year of Darius I (520 BC). Mentioned also in Ezra 5:1, 6:14.',
