    faithJourney:
      "Sanballat's relationship to Israel's God is complicated by the fact that he may have considered himself a worshiper. The Samaritans — the community Sanballat represented — claimed their own version of Yahweh worship centered on Mount Gerizim rather than Jerusalem. His daughter married into the Jewish high-priestly family (Nehemiah 13:28), which suggests he saw some continuity between his community's faith and Judah's. He wasn't necessarily opposing God; he was opposing a specific political project led by people who claimed exclusive divine authorization.\n\nThat said, the text presents his opposition as opposition to God's purposes, and his methods — mockery, threats, deception, political manipulation — are not the tools of someone operating in good faith. Sanballat's story is a cautionary portrait of what happens when self-interest wraps itself in legitimate grievances. He may have had real concerns about Jerusalem's growing power. He may have had valid questions about Nehemiah's authority. But his willingness to lie, threaten, and scheme reveals that preserving his position mattered more than any principle he might have invoked. His faith, whatever its content, was subordinate to his politics.",
    sourceTier: 'ai_assisted',
