    faithJourney:
      "Tobiah's name — which ironically means \"the LORD is good\" — suggests a family with at least nominal ties to Yahweh worship. His marriage connections to Jewish families indicate he moved in circles where Israel's faith was practiced, even if his own commitment was strategic rather than sincere. He represents a type that every religious community knows: the person who speaks the language, attends the events, and maintains the relationships, but whose actual loyalty is to their own influence rather than to the community's stated values.\n\nThe most telling detail about Tobiah's relationship to sacred things is the temple room. Getting a personal chamber in the house of God — displacing the tithes and offerings that belonged there — wasn't an accident or an oversight. It was the logical endpoint of treating a faith community as a networking opportunity. When Nehemiah threw his furniture out and had the room purified, he was making a statement about the difference between being in the building and belonging to the purpose the building was built for. Tobiah had the access but never had the allegiance, and the text suggests that the community's willingness to blur that distinction was itself part of the problem Nehemiah had been sent to fix.",
